Lesson 3 = Crazy Czech Consonants! üá®üáø Pronunciation & Czech Alphabet ====================================================================================================================================================================
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v8udpCkbW1Q&list=PLa-iOaRNqZBx4H7bAmMvDEzr94yG0y6Ub&index=4&ab_channel=CzechwithKate%C5%99ina
Lots of pronunciation practice in this - going to take some time to get that down - If I can learn Japanese, this shouldn't be as bad - 
Consants in Czech are divided into 3 easy groups :
  Hard = H / CH / K / R / D / T / N 
  Soft = C / ƒå / J / ≈ò / ≈† / ≈Ω / ƒé
  Ambiguous = B / F / L / M / P / S / V / Z
Ch = sounds like 'He'
C = 'Tz'ar or Pre'Tz'el sounds like 'Tz'
ƒå = sounds like 'Ch' 'Cz'ech 'Ch'eese 
J = sounds like 'Ya' 'Ya'wn 'Yo'u
≈ò = ? Zhu? Je? Haju? sounds like R + Z in one 'RZ'
≈† = sounds like 'Sh' 'Sh'arp 'Sh'adow
≈Ω = Sounds like 'Su' mea'su're ca'su'ally
ƒé = sounds like a soft 'D'
≈§ = sounds like a soft 'T'
≈á = sounds like a soft 'N' - 'nieu' ca'ny'on 
B / F / L / M / P / S / V / Z = sound like their English versions, 
G / X / Q / W = Do not belong to any group of consonants, appear in Czech language only, will learn more about these later.
Y = Hard 'I' = If Consonant Preceding is soft or hard, if hard use 'Y'
I = Soft 'I' = If Consonant Preceding is soft or hard, if soft use 'I'



















